etween natural, youthful passion and the gentry's pragmatic view of marriage; the problems of King Arthur's marriage in light of bothpolitical need and the difficulty of the queen's infertility and adultery; and the repercussions of Lancelot's adultery in the tragedies of two marriageable daughters, Elaine of Astolat and Elaine of Corbin. Finally, the author reveals and considers in detail (focusing on dynastic dysfunction in three generations of Pendragon men: Uther, Arthur and Mordred) the myth of benevolent paternity by which men, whether born legitimate of bastard, were united through the Round Table. KAREN CHEREWATUK is Professor of English at St Olaf College, Minnesota.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAdultery in literature. 0aArthurian romancesxHistory and criticism. 0aInheritance and succession in literature. 0aMarriage in literature. 0aRomances, EnglishxHistory and criticism. 4aMedieval Literature. 4aWomen's & Gender Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aArthur.  aBritish gentry.  aMiddle Ages.  aMordred.  aPendragon men.  aUther.  aadultery.  adynastic dysfunction.  aheirs.  aland.  amarriage.  anobility.  apolitical rule.  apower.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781846154898?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846154898423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781846154898/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles